is, France","Picardy, France":"Picardie, France","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni":"Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Fontaines","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Normand, Pierre, Emile, Fernand, Lucien, Marcel, Adelard, Henri, Jacques, Laurent.","French and Walloon: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, from Old French <i>fontaine</i>, from Late Latin <i>fontana</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>fons</i> (see   Font  ); or a habitational name from Fontaine, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Fountaine  .","Shortened form of French   Lafontaine  , a variant of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Fontenot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Ulysse, Andrus, Alcide, Andre, Edouard, Lucien, Marise, Monique, Remy.","French: variant of <b>Fonteneau</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from any of several places mainly in the westcentral part of France so named. The surname <i>Fontenot</i> is very rare in France.","History: Jean-Louis Fonteneau/Fontenot from Montierneuf in Vienne, France, married Louise-Angélique Henry in Mobile, AL, in 1726."]},{"name":"Fontenelle","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from (La) Fontenelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fontenette","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from Fontenette, the name of several places mainly in the central part of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fountain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from one or more of the places in France named Fontaine, Fonteyne, or Lafontaine (see   Fontaine  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or well, from Middle English <i>fontayne</i> (Old French <i>fontaine</i>) ‘spring, fountain’, sometimes with a plural <i>-s</i>, and synonymous with   Well  , of which <i>Fountain(es)</i> may sometimes have been a translation."]},{"name":"Font","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Miguel, Rafael, Eduardo, Raul, Eugenio, Pedro, Roberto, Aida.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, Catalan and Occitan <i>font</i> ‘spring, well’ (from Latin <i>fons</i>, genitive <i>fontis</i>).","English: variant of   Fant  ."]},{"name":"Fontan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Angel, Benigno, Carlos, Jose, Juana, Manuel, Pedro, Adolfo, Aida, Alfredo, Candido, Emilia.","Spanish and Galician (<b>Fontán</b>): habitational name from any of the many places called Fontán, from <i>fontán</i> ‘spring’.","French: variant of   Fontaine  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde de Fontaines was born in 1190, in Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Aléaume de Fontaines, was 28 and her mother, Laure DE SAINT-VALERY, was 31. She married Hugues De Bailleul III in 1210. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1252, in Bailleul, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1190–1252":"1190–1252","1184–1238":"1184–1238","–1164":"–1164","–1202":"–1202","–1214":"–1214","–1233":"–1233","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud"